### [Docker Sandboxes: Run Agents in YOLO Mode, Safely](https://www.docker.com/blog/docker-sandboxes-run-agents-in-yolo-mode-safely/) — Docker Blog  
Docker Sandboxes provide a hard boundary around autonomous agents, preventing file‑system leaks or destructive commands. By defining limits outside the agent code, the sandbox reduces the attack surface and allows teams to safely prototype and scale code‑generation pipelines without exposing critical data. The sandbox runs natively on local machines, supporting agents such as Claude Code, GitHub Copilot CLI, Gemini CLI, and upcoming NanoClaw and OpenClaw, and it yields a 60 % lift in pull‑request merge rates for teams that run agents autonomously.

### [Holo3: Breaking the Computer Use Frontier](https://huggingface.co/blog/Hcompany/holo3) — Hugging Face Blog  
Holo3 is a 10‑B active‑parameter enterprise agent that scores 78.85 % on the OSWorld‑Verified desktop‑use benchmark while keeping inference cost below GPT‑5.4. Its “agentic learning flywheel” blends synthetic navigation data, out‑of‑domain augmentation, and curated reinforcement learning, feeding a 486‑task suite of real‑world enterprise scenarios. The open‑source 35‑B variant and free‑tier API lower the barrier to experimentation, enabling Kubernetes‑based MLOps stacks to deploy domain‑specific agents with minimal compute footprints.

### [Falcon Perception](https://huggingface.co/blog/tiiuae/falcon-perception) — Hugging Face Blog  
Falcon Perception is a 0.6‑B transformer that jointly encodes image patches and language prompts, generating instance masks, coordinates, and size tokens in a single backbone. Hybrid attention lets image tokens attend bidirectionally to build global visual context, while text tokens attend causally over the visual prefix and prior text, yielding a shared encoder‑decoder architecture. On the open‑vocabulary SA‑Co benchmark it achieves 68.0 % macro‑F1, outperforming SAM 3, and the lightweight design cuts GPU usage by ~3× on a single A100 when served with vLLM.

### [Granite 4.0 3B Vision](https://huggingface.co/blog/ibm-granite/granite-4-vision) — Hugging Face Blog  
Granite 4.0 3B Vision is a LoRA adapter atop Granite 4.0 Micro that supports both text‑only and multimodal workloads. Its ChartNet dataset of 1.7 M synthetic charts and DeepStack visual‑feature injection enable simultaneous semantic and spatial understanding. The model scores 86.4 % on Chart2Summary, 85.5 % on VAREX KVP, and leads on PubTablesV2 TEDS, all with only 3 B parameters. The lightweight VLM can be deployed as a single microservice on Kubernetes, integrating with Docling for full‑page PDF pipelines while maintaining high‑accuracy extraction at lower compute cost.

